00:00:19,134 --> 00:00:21,790
Now, let's talk about What is Edge Computing?

6
00:00:21,790 --> 00:00:23,437
(The Simple Explanation).

7
00:00:23,437 --> 00:00:26,526
Imagine you're in Mumbai, ordering food from Swiggy.

8
00:00:26,526 --> 00:00:28,930
The restaurant is 2 km away.

9
00:00:28,930 --> 00:00:37,512
But what if, instead of the nearby restaurant preparing your food, Swiggy sent your order to a kitchen in New York, and then flew the prepared food back to you?

10
00:00:37,512 --> 00:00:39,038
That would be insane, right?

11
00:00:39,038 --> 00:00:42,536
But that's essentially what happens with traditional cloud computing.

12
00:00:42,536 --> 00:00:50,300
When you use an app, your request often travels thousands of kilometers to a data center, gets processed, and travels back.

13
00:00:50,300 --> 00:00:53,930
Edge computing brings the processing closer to you.

14
00:00:53,930 --> 00:00:55,096
Why Does This Matter?.

15
00:00:55,096 --> 00:00:57,187
Speed of Light is the Limit

16
00:00:57,187 --> 00:01:02,271
Light travels at ~300,000 km/second.

17
00:01:02,271 --> 00:01:08,485
That sounds fast, but: Mumbai to US-East: ~14,000 km.

18
00:01:08,485 --> 00:01:13,413
One-way time: ~47ms (just light travel, no processing).

19
00:01:13,413 --> 00:01:18,064
Real-world with network hops: ~100-150ms one-way.

20
00:01:18,064 --> 00:01:21,971
For many applications, this delay is unacceptable.

21
00:01:21,971 --> 00:01:25,156
Moving on to The Latency Problem (With Real Numbers).

